	Calcutta: Veteran sports journalist Moti Nandi passed away at a private hospital on Sunday. 
  He was 79 and is survived by wife and three daughters. Nandi had been keeping unwell for sometime, and died of ldquo;a massive cardiac arrest, rdquo; according to a release from the hospital. 
  A former sports editor of Ananda Bazar Patrika, he used his vast experience in sports journalism in scripting award winning novels.    
	Sydney: Former Australian captain Steve Waugh, along with four others, would be inducted into the International Cricket Council's Hall of Fame here Monday. Australian cricket legends Victor Trumper, Bill O rsquo;Reilly, Keith Miller and Ray Lindwall will be inducted posthumously.     
	Zurich: Peter Sauber, owner of Formula One team Sauber has told a Swiss paper he is planning to stay involved in the sport in the medium to long term. He said that his planning stretches to the next three to five years.    
	London: World No. 4 Andy Murray has withdrawn from Britain rsquo;s Davis Cup tie against Lithuania in March and will in future discuss his participation with the Lawn Tennis Association before every match. ldquo;We have talented young players who need Davis Cup experience to help with their career development, rdquo; Murray was quoted as saying in a British website Saturday.  
